text.tspan: So, you're hosting regions on your local network. Outside people
can connect to them, but you can't. Why?

text.textPath: REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63 REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63 REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63 REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63

flowRoot.flowPara: Your region reports its IP as your internet IP, so that it may communicate with the outside world
Your viewer asks for your region's IP, which the grid gives as your internet IP
Your viewer broadcasts "UDP" packets to your region, attempting a "handshake" to tell the region you're going in
Your router reports UDP broadcasts to your own internet IP as "unreachable", thus your region never receives the broadcasts.

text.textPath: REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63 REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63 REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63 REGION IS AT 207.69.128.63

flowRoot.flowPara: Your viewer is configured to tunnel through a SOCKS5 proxy, in this case UDProxy. Normal UDP traffic flow through it untouched
UDProxy detects UDP broadcasts to your internet IP and redirects them to your region's local IP
